metadata.name: Mordāb #88
metadata.description:
In Farsi, 'Mordāb' translates to 'marshes,' embodying both tranquility and mystery within nature. The term also carries the meaning of 'dead waters,' yet paradoxically, marshes are teeming with life. This project, meticulously crafted with minimalist dots, draws inspiration from ampersionism techniques, creating a seamless fusion of realism and fantasy. Utilizing a palette of serene, realistic hues alongside vibrant, imaginative shades, I envisioned a space where one could truly wander, dream, and embrace the paradoxical vitality of marshes. Chill, dream, and let your thoughts wander amidst the captivating allure of nature.

Please press ‘2’ to ‘5’ to change the resolution (max 7500 × 6000 px).*
Use the key ’S’ to save the output as a PNG file.
Use the key ’T’ to deactivate texture overlay for high quality printing.
*Higher resolutions may cause your browser to freeze for a while.

metadata.name: Abstract Calligraphy #50
metadata.description:
This work is inspired by Japanese avant-garde calligraphy (前衛書 Zenei-sho, or 墨象 Boku-shou). After World War II, the art of Japanese calligraphy was rapidly modernized. The ultimate result was avant-garde calligraphy that did not depict characters. They resembled the works of contemporary Western paintings of the same period, such as Abstract Expressionism and Art informel. In fact, some of the avant-garde calligraphy works were drawn with oil paint on canvas instead of Sumi ink on paper. So what is the difference between painting and calligraphy in those works?
A founder of avant-garde calligraphy said that the artistic essence of calligraphy art lies in the expression of a well-honed brushstroke, so the materials used are merely a medium. Then, is it possible for computer-drawn Bezier curves to become calligraphy art? This is an experiment in that.

This work is interactive. Clicking on the image or pressing the "m" key on the keyboard will randomly transform the shape of the strokes. There are 10 types of brushes. You can switch to other brushes by pressing the number keys on the keyboard (Touch devices switch with the direction of the swipe).
In addition, the strokes resize responsively to the window size, but the shape of the brush remains the same, so you can enjoy a different look by changing the screen's aspect ratio.

metadata.name: Infinite Rhythmic Universe - PROTOTYPE #3
metadata.description:
This is a prototype that generates rhythm patterns for samplers and FM synthesized sounds in web audio. Various shapes are generated reactively according to the tone according to the sound.

There are some audio post-processes available as parameters, and they are also working as visual post-processes at the same time.

metadata.name: Flowers and Sky #52
metadata.description:
Flowers and Sky

Using natural brushstrokes and bright colors, this generative system creates stunning scenes of flower-filled meadows under a brilliant sky. It is inspired by the masters of impressionist art and aims to capture the beauty of nature.

Every leaf, petal, cloud, and sunray are generated from code using simulated brushstrokes. The flowers and trees are suggestive only and do not depict real species.

There are 8 formal features that have many values in order to generate a wide variety of outputs. The only rare feature is a SkyMode of 'Eclipse' which occurs in 3% of the outputs.

--------------------------

This is a 100% code generated project. Outputs are created at a default resolution of 1500 x 1000.

Click on the output and use these keys to change the resolution or save the output:
's' - save at current resolution

'2' - change to  3000 x 2000 resolution
'3' - change to  4500 x 3000 resolution
...
'8' - change to 12000 x 8000 resolution

URL Parameters: You can also set the resolution in the url.
To change the resolution append &res=2 (or 3-8)

Copyright 2023 Jeff Clark

metadata.name: Henoheno Samurai #2827
metadata.description:
This work was inspired by Otsu-e(大津絵), a Japanese painting in the Edo period. Otsu-e were inexpensive paintings made as souvenirs. Although mass-produced using paper stencils, the artisans painted by hand, resulting in variations in the quality of their work. Connoisseurs found them interesting and collected them as works of art. Otsu-e showed a new value of beauty in Japanese art, different from Ukiyo-e (浮世絵) which are prints, and from fine art paintings which are one-of-a-kind artworks.

This work is made of canvas2D Bezier curves. Not just a combination of parts, but also a random displacement of the Bezier curve points to lose the shape. This is intended to create fun with the Otsu-e-like effect.


Features:
This profile is made up of 8 parts (brows, eyes, nose, mouth, ear, contour, hair, and body). Each part has 100 basic types. 
There are 7 skin colors and 12 kimono colors. Each RGB value of the colors is randomly added within a range of ±10. In addition, there are 70 kimono patterns. 
The distortion rate due to displacement of Bezier curve points is 0.0~50.0. 


BTW The title "Henoheno" is taken from the Japanese character picture "Henohenomoheji" known since the Edo period.

metadata.name: Square Planets #199
metadata.description:
Square Planets was inspired by a series of OP Art paintings done by Victor Vasarely, called Planetary Folklore Participations No. 2. (c. 1970). Vasarely died in 1997 in the early days of computer art. I'm sure he would have embraced this medium. This is the third in a series of Vasarely inspired Generative Art pieces I am offering.

I became interested in Victor Vasarely's graphic artworks while I was in art school. As I struggled to learn computer graphics I wondered how do I write a program to produce imagery with a similar aesthetic? I call the process of creating algorithms inspired by other artists: "Art"ificial Intelligence.

Square Planets consists of four layers of squares contained within a background square superimposed on top of one another. Each layer is translated from the previous layer but still lies within its boundaries. The background color of each layer is random and its set of squares are another random color. The squares that make up layers two and three are rotated either clockwise or counter-clockwise some random number of degrees within a predetermined range. 

There are many Gestalt interactions within this piece. Layers (square planets) interact with each other in interesting ways. Each new generation with its random color assignments significantly affect your depth perception. Layers appear to come forward or recede. Sometimes there is more "after-imagism" between the square sets. Candy for your mind.

objkt.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #146

metadata.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #146
metadata.description:
Experimental generative collection that merges analog photography, AI, generative text, and algorithmic coding, by digging down into the essence and building blocks of the different artistic communication channels. 

This work engages with all aforementioned mediums in a joint manner, guided by a random process. It starts with a collection of analog photographs, shot on film and scanned that were later used as a training dataset in Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) training. This way, A.I. learns the main characteristics of film photography. In particular, it mimics its recognizable grain. Another type of pixel grain is added with the use of code and pixel shifting as well as digital manipulation. Finally, the last type of “grain” appears with the use of generative text where a different kind of A.I. was given a short description of the project and instructed to imagine the rest of the story. The fragmented and void of meaning parts of generative text are added to the images as one of the possible traits.

issuer.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I.

metadata.name: The Face We Had #253
metadata.description:
The Face We Had is a series of generative, moving sculptures attempting to express the artists personal thoughts, experiences and inclinations related to meditative and altered states of consciousness. In a non-descriptive way, the piece aims to reflect the always changing nature of mind through patterns of movement and assemblages of form, color and organic shapes, endlessly revolving around a perceived point of origin.  

Although not intended as literal depictions, the elements interact in a way that could be interpreted as dance-like interactions between thought patterns, mental energy, feelings, fragments of memories and layers of personal identity. 



Interactive features:

space - pause/play
w - wireframe view
d - debug view (compute textures)
s - save screenshot

metadata.name: Circonvolution #58
metadata.description:
Circonvolution is a French word meaning "wrapped around" but also "twists and turns".
In this project, several vortexes drive colors in a chaotic winding path whose final look is sometimes quite organic.

Depending on the computer, the calculation time may be about ten seconds.
---
To save, type:
[1] at 2000x2000 px
To save in high resolution, (can be long)
[2] at 4000x6000 px 
[3] at 6000x6000 px

---

100% done with p5js
Some colors are from "A Dictionary of Color Combinations" by Wada Sanzō
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

Hervé (Jan 23)

metadata.name: views #50
metadata.description:
views is an animated generative art collection inspired on my morning walks by the beach, enjoying the mediterranean sea and the view of Barcelona coast. 
in the attempt to go further than the eye can see, i have tried to simplify the visuals. using only the waves as fundamental, i find myself experimenting with order, chaos, mutability and the tendency of systems to entropy. 

this is my first attempt to use fxparams in a collection. i encourage the collector/co-creator to play for a while with the params i provide, it is quite impressive the different results that we obtain with a few changes. ranges are quite wide so use them carefully. 
!WARNING! to have the transparency effect on waves i use in the preview, select low alpha range on background color
params:
- lines distance (2-40).
- lines speed (1-3).
- strokeweight (0.5-50).
- waves interval (40-300).
- waves pattern: sinusoidal, noise, random, gradual (3 types depending on the hash), none.
- mmmm (0-5).
- coils (0-5).
- pen color. 
- background color.

interaction:
- adaptable to screen size. BETTER enjoy it on fullscreen.
CAUTION: features will adjust to screen size.
- press 's' to save an image.
- click mouse to stop animation.
- double-click to restart animation.

made with p5js and love
mekhno / Marc L Clapers
